{{Infobox mountain pass | name = Gate of Trajan | photo =Крепост Траянови Врата - 2015-09-02.jpg | photo_caption = Remnants of the Trajan's Gate fortress | elevation_m = 800 | elevation_ref = | traversed = [[Trakiya motorway]] | location = [[Bulgaria]] | range = | coordinates = {{coord|42|21|22|N|23|55|6|E|type:pass_region:BG}} | topo = }} The '''Gate of Trajan''' or '''Trajan's Gate''' ({{lang-bg|Траянови врата}}, ''Trayanovi vrata'') is a historic mountain pass near [[Ihtiman]], [[Bulgaria]]. It was named so after [[Roman Emperor]] [[Trajan]], on whose order a fortress by the name of ''Stipon'' was constructed on the hill over the pass, as a symbolic border between the [[Roman province|provinces]] of [[Thrace]] and [[Macedonia (Roman province)|Macedonia]].
The pass is primarily known for the [[Battle of the Gates of Trajan|major medieval battle]] of 17 August 986, during which the forces of [[Byzantine Emperor]] [[Basil II]] were routed by [[List of Bulgarian monarchs|Tsar]] [[Samuil of Bulgaria]], effectively halting a Byzantine campaign in the Bulgarian lands.<ref>Jim Bradbury, ''The Routledge Companion to Medieval Warfare'', (Taylor & Francis, 2005), 178</ref>
Today, a tunnel of [[Trakiya motorway]] similarly known as the Gate of Trajan Tunnel (тунел „Траянови врата“) is near the fortress, {{convert|55|km|mi}} from [[Sofia]].
The [[Saddle (landform)|saddle]] [[Trajan Gate]] on [[Graham Land]] in [[Antarctica]] is named after the Gate of Trajan.
